04529nam a22005415i 9780226196503DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014010889  a9780226196503  a(DE-B1597)550035  a(OCoLC)894668662  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHM656b.W35 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh  aMS 12902rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123589:1 aWajcman, Judy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPressed for Time :bThe Acceleration of Life in Digital Capitalism /cJudy Wajcman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Tools for Time -- t1. High-Speed Society: Is the Pace of Life Accelerating? -- t2. Time and Motion: Machines and the Making of Modernity -- t3. The Time-Pressure Paradox -- t4. Working with Constant Connectivity -- t5. Doing Domestic Time -- t6. Time to Talk: Intimacy through Technology -- t7. Finding Time in a Digital Age -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe technologically tethered, iPhone-addicted figure is an image we can easily conjure. Most of us complain that there aren't enough hours in the day and too many e-mails in our thumb-accessible inboxes. This widespread perception that life is faster than it used to be is now ingrained in our culture, and smartphones and the Internet are continually being blamed. But isn't the sole purpose of the smartphone to give us such quick access to people and information that we'll be free to do other things? Isn't technology supposed to make our lives easier? In Pressed for Time, Judy Wajcman explains why we immediately interpret our experiences with digital technology as inexorably accelerating everyday life. She argues that we are not mere hostages to communication devices, and the sense of always being rushed is the result of the priorities and parameters we ourselves set rather than the machines that help us set them. Indeed, being busy and having action-packed lives has become valorized by our productivity driven culture. Wajcman offers a bracing historical perspective, exploring the commodification of clock time, and how the speed of the industrial age became identified with progress. She also delves into the ways time-use differs for diverse groups in modern societies, showing how changes in work patterns, family arrangements, and parenting all affect time stress. Bringing together empirical research on time use and theoretical debates about dramatic digital developments, this accessible and engaging book will leave readers better versed in how to use technology to navigate life's fast lane.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 0aTime perceptionxSocial aspects. 0aTime pressure. 0aTimexSociological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acapitalist, government, economy, economics, finance, financial, money, wealth, life, daily, technology, iphone, computer, laptop, communication, culture, cultural, email, accessibility, internet, smartphone, digital, online, devices, productivity, social studies, perception, time, sociology, innovation, invention, stress, productive.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226196503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226196503/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyte